# UPSTREAM-FIXES.patch
#
# Upstream bug fixes for the FireAlt.VFXForge package (com.firealt.vfx-forge,
# github IAFahim/com.firealt.vfx-forge). These were authored against the
# resolved package cache and MUST be re-applied to the real com.firealt.vfx-forge
# repository (PackageCache edits are wiped on package re-resolve).
#
# Apply from the com.firealt.vfx-forge repo root with:
#     git apply UPSTREAM-FIXES.patch
# (paths are repo-relative, a/b prefixed; use -p1). If applying against a working
# copy that has drifted, `git apply --3way` or `patch -p1 < UPSTREAM-FIXES.patch`.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FIXES IN THIS PATCH (maps to BovineLabs.Timeline.VFXForge/TODO.md items)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# [1] C3 - InitializeVFXSystem duplicate-key error loop.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/InitializeVFXSystem.cs
#     On a failed TryAddVFXEntry (e.g. duplicate VFXKey), still disable
#     HybridVisualEffectData (initializeRW = false) so the entity is not
#     re-processed every frame. RegisteredVFX.Key is left at VFXKey.Null, which
#     CleanupVFXSystem already skips (verified: `if (Key.Equals(VFXKey.Null)) continue;`).
#     Result: the error logs once, not per-frame.
#
# [2] H8 - Burst violation: Application.isPlaying inside [BurstCompile] SyncVFXSystem.OnUpdate/AddVFX.
#     Files: FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/SyncVFXSystem.cs
#            FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/SyncVFXSystem.Managed.cs
#     Added a `SharedStatic<bool> IsPlaying` (IsPlayingContext) alongside the
#     existing SharedStatic pattern. It is written ONLY from managed code - seeded
#     in OnCreate (SyncVFXSystem.Managed.cs, not [BurstCompile]) and refreshed at
#     the top of the managed UploadDataPacked - never from the struct static ctor
#     (which may run under Burst). The Burst OnUpdate / AddVFX now read
#     Burst.IsPlaying.Data instead of Application.isPlaying. UploadDataPacked runs
#     at the END of OnUpdate, so OnUpdate reads the prior frame's value (or the
#     OnCreate seed on frame 0); a one-frame-stale flag across the play-mode
#     transition is acceptable. Managed partial code keeps reading
#     Application.isPlaying directly (fine there).
#
# [3] Medium - HasRequiredProperties log-once.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Singletons/VFXGraphicsBuffersSingleton.cs
#     Added `private bool _loggedFailure;` on VFXGraphicsBuffers. The try/catch now
#     logs the exception only on the first failure and still returns false every
#     time; the flag resets on a successful validation. The checks themselves run
#     every call, so the return value stays accurate - only the per-frame logging
#     is suppressed.
#
# [4] Medium - SyncVFXSystem.OnDestroy teardown guards.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/SyncVFXSystem.cs
#     OnDestroy used GetSingleton for both singletons, which throws if the
#     singleton entities were destroyed first during world teardown (leaking the
#     Persistent-allocator containers). Now uses ManagedAPI.TryGetSingleton /
#     TryGetSingleton guards, disposes only what exists, and always disposes
#     _stateChanges (guarded by IsCreated).
#
# [5] Low - Version-wrap skip-0.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/SyncVFXSystem.cs
#     After `Burst.VFXSystemVersion.Data++`, skip a value that masks to 0 in the
#     30-bit version field: `if ((Data & 0x3FFFFFFF) == 0) Data++;`. Mask verified
#     against PackedData.cs (VALUE_BITS = 30, SYSTEM_VERSION_MASK = 0x3FFFFFFF).
#     SystemVersion == 0 is TryResolve's dead/Null sentinel, so a valid handle must
#     never carry it after wrap.
#
# [6] Medium - VFXTransformSystem fill/consume assertions.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Systems/VFXTransformSystem.cs
#     The main-thread fill loop always appends SpawnEntityIdRequests to
#     EntityIdFrameData, but FetchGameObjectTransformJob consumes them only when
#     entry.HasPendingRequests, sharing running index `i` with TrackedEntityIds.
#     Added two Burst-compatible Unity.Assertions.Assert guards:
#       - at fill time: HasPendingRequests || SpawnEntityIdRequests.Length == 0
#       - at end of FetchGameObjectTransformJob.Execute: i == EntityIdFrameData.Length
#         (trivially holds 0 == 0 when no EntityId work existed).
#
# [7] C2 defense-in-depth - MemClear stale data slot. CHOKE POINT: the private
#     base PersistentVFXEntry.Spawn(TrackedEntity, float), clearing DeferredDataBuffer.
#     File: FireAlt.VFXForge/Entry/PersistentVFXEntry.cs
#     REASONING for the single choke point (confirmed by reading
#     ResolvePersistentJob.SpawnPersistentRequests in SyncVFXSystem.cs):
#       - DeferredDataBuffer.IsCreated  <=>  DataSizeInBytes > 0  <=>  DataBuffer.IsCreated
#         (all three are allocated together in InitializeVFXSystem only when
#          entry.DataSizeInBytes > 0).
#       - When DeferredDataBuffer.IsCreated, resolution ALWAYS routes through
#         internalApi.SpawnPersistentUnsafe(ptr = DeferredDataBuffer slot), which
#         MemCpys that slot into DataBuffer. The non-Unsafe InternalAPI.SpawnPersistent
#         is reached ONLY in the else-branch, i.e. when DeferredDataBuffer is NOT
#         created (DataSizeInBytes == 0) - so it has no data buffer to clear and a
#         MemClear there (the TODO's option a) would be dead code.
#       - Therefore the one place that fixes BOTH the direct-DataBuffer staleness and
#         the deferred staleness is clearing the DeferredDataBuffer slot in the
#         private base Spawn. Data-less spawns (the timeline VFXForgeClip's
#         Spawn(target, 0f)) never write it, so the slot retains a previous
#         occupant's bytes that would flow DeferredDataBuffer -> DataBuffer -> GPU.
#         The typed (Spawn<T>) and unsafe (SpawnUnsafe) overloads call this private
#         Spawn FIRST and then overwrite the slot with real data, so clearing then
#         overwriting is correct and cheap. Each spawn owns a unique IndexInData via
#         Interlocked NextIndex, so the per-slot MemClear is race-free under the
#         parallel SpawnJob.
#     Uses the file's existing unsafe pointer idiom
#     ((byte*)DeferredDataBuffer.GetUnsafePtr() + IndexInData * DataSizeInBytes) with
#     UnsafeUtility.MemClear; the private Spawn is marked `unsafe`.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
